				<td colspan="2"><span>This is a very interesting thread indeed. 
<br />
   I like what you guys have had to say about this so I want to throw a few pennies in too while there's still water in the well. I'm 23 and I've been playing EQ off and on for over 4 years. I defenitely have to agree that more good things have happened to me when I break from it than when I sit in my room and grind for 6-10 hours a day. I'm not saying this to preach I'm saying it because for me it's a fact of life. Now, I still played EQ up until about a month ago when my roomate started playing WoW, which is what I now play. When we quit EQ I was playing every 4-5 days for maybe an hour or two at a time, whenever I didn't have anything to do really. Since getting WoW my roomate has lost his job, smokes REDICULOUS amounts of ganj, (and come on now I love my spinach too but some things are more important, like putting pants on) hasn't taken the trash out or fed the cats in 2 weeks and hasn't washed a dish in the sink in the same amount of time. 
<br />
    I know what's going on and it's not completely due to video games, I'm not here to blame my dirty dishes on Blizzard.  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" />
<br />
    It's the nature of the beast, some people are affected by online games more than others. Since I stopped playing EQ I met an amazing girl, bought a new jeep and took a vacation to Alaska. I didn't get up one day and say &quot;let's see what happens if I don't play EQ&quot; it just happened. I play WoW on weekends mostly, and that's if I have time, but I would probably be sitting at my house playing right now if I hadn't met my girlfriend at a buddy's party by chance. 
<br />
   I agree with the starter of this thread on one thing only, I hate preachy people so I'm not trying to do that, rather I wanted to share my experiences with similar problems. For some people it just takes a jumpstart to get back into life, for others it takes a free fall. 
<br />

<br />
What can I say man people are inherently lacking, not to get into philosophy or psychology but some people just need <i>something</i> and 90% of the time they don't even understand why. I don't think anyone here could tell me they've gone through life feeling complete at all times. Not that anyone needs a video game to feel complete, but it sure takes your mind off it doesn't it?
<br />
